== English ==
=== Etymology ===
# {{philosophy}} from [[French]] ''[[mauvaise foi]]'' (literally, bad faith), coined by [[existentialist]] [[philosopher]] [[w:Jean-Paul Sarte|Jean-Paul Sarte]].
# [[bad]] + [[faith]]

=== Noun ===
{{en-noun|-}}
# {{philosophy}} the [[existentialist]] concept of denying one's total [[free will|freedom of will]]<ref>[[w:Bad faith (existentialism)|Bad faith (existentialism)]] (Wikipedia)</ref>.
# {{law}} a malicious motive by a party in a lawsuit. This has an effect on the ability to maintain causes of action and obtain legal remedies<ref>[[w:Bad faith|Bad faith]] (Wikipedia)</ref>.
# {{law}} intent to [[deceive]] or [[mislead]] another to gain some advantage; [[dishonesty]] or [[fraud]] in a transaction (such as knowingly misrepresenting the quality of something that is being bought or sold)<ref>[http://www.lectlaw.com/def/b001.htm "Bad Faith" Defined] (The 'Lectric Law Library)</ref>.

